bioghist.head: Biographical Sketch
bioghist.p: Born in Coolidge, Limestone County, Texas, William Curry Holden attended high school in Rotan, Texas. He received B.A., M.A., and Ph.D. from the University of Texas at Austin, and then went on to teach history at McMurry College (1923-1927) in Abilene, Texas, the University of Texas (1927-1928) at Austin, and Texas Technological College (1928-1965) in Lubbock, Texas. At Texas Technological College, Holden served as professor of History, Sociology, and Anthropology, Dean of Archaeological and Social Science, and Dean of the Graduate School. He was granted the status of Professor Emeritus of History in 1965, and was instrumental in the establishment of the Southwest Collection and the Texas Tech Museum. Dr. Holden passed away in April 1993.

William Holden married Frances Virginia Mayhugh on March 26, 1939. She received an M.A. in history at Texas Tech in 1940 and served as associate director of its museum from 1940 to 1965. She founded the museum's Southwestern Art Collection and the Women's Council of the West Texas Museum Association. Mrs. Holden passed away in August 2007.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection includes correspondence, financial material, research material, and literary productions pertaining to Holden's career as a teacher, writer, and administrator. Also includes personal correspondence, scrapbook material, research notes, rough drafts and correspondence realted to his scholarly publications. Of particular interest is a collection of diaries written by Dr. Holden's students during an archaeological field expedition to Mexico.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: The majority of the collection is open for use except the following restricted files:

Financial Material in (Boxes 15-23), Financial Material contained under the Mayhugh Family (Boxes 65-66), and History Department Grade Sheets (Box 24-25, 29-30). Please consult the archivist of record for permission to examine the materials.
